Basketball brought me back to Ohio for @playbyplayclassics2022 

When first started coaching I thought I would never leave Boston. I never knew basketball would take me to so many wonderful places and meet so many amazing people. 

Worked with Dave Spiller for 14 amazing years . We had the best working relationship. I would hope other assistants could get along like we did.

Fortunate to have Brian Donoher with me at Wright State. Tony Ortiz and Mike Zink are as loyal and caring as they come! 

It was special to spend time with two legendary  coaches in Joe Petrocelli and  the Dayton Flyer HOF Don Donoher. 

Lived 12 in Columbus and Dayton Ohio for twelve years. Had two incredible basketball experiences. 🏀

Along the way we met some amazing folks. I call them friends.❤️ 

Our youngest daughter was born in the Ohio State Hospital. We made time to drive by the houses we lived in. 🏡

Don’t take basketball for granted. An orange ball, a group of coaches and special teammates can make life special. It was great to be back!

The City of Palms was hotly contested with super competitive teams! It was filled with an abundance of ranked teams and great players. I came away impressed by the coaches too! 

This list was earned!

On Tuesday, February 7th shortly after 9 PM ET we got the call. My mom had transitioned to be with God. It was peaceful with family and Hathorne Hill workers at her side. At 93 her health was declining. But earlier in the afternoon it seemed like a normal day. 

My sister Elaine was visiting her and brought her a slice of pizza. Elaine would  send me a text to Facetime when they were together. It doesn’t matter where I was or what I was doing, I made the call. I was boarding a flight and FaceTimed before we took off. 

She left a legacy of unconditional love, ultimate sacrafice, inner strength and unselfishness. 

You don’t get to 93 without living a life of great habits. 

Her constant advice was “everything in moderation.” “Including moderation!”

Hours before she passed. The FaceTime call ended with me saying “I love you mom” and her blowing me a kiss. 

There is a void that never will be replaced and there is much to process. Gratefulness will win out. ❤️ 

Missing you and loving you, Mom. We all are. ✝️

More on Gloria Biancardi on my FaceBook.

Analysis: 

Holland is an NBA athlete with great bounce and open court speed to convert when 
the game goes up and down. His personality and mindset are to outwork his opponent, put winning first and make defense a priority each game. He is also a great switch defender which the NBA covets in their evaluation of prospects. Holland scores in many ways both inside the paint and on the perimeter.
 
As a true multi-dimensional player Holland jumped up to No.2 overall in our final rankings. If his growth continues, he is on track to be a top five pick in the 2024 NBA draft with a lengthy career and the potential of an NBA All-star.
 
Throughout  his career he played with consistent effort and high energy. He established himself as a defender early in his career and finished as the best one on one defender in the class. 

His offensive game is a blend of transition baskets, offensive rebound put backs, off ball cuts, dribble drives and open jumpers that extend to the 3pt line. 

He started out high on my board and finished at No. 2 in the Final ESPN 100 player rankings for the class of 2023.

Roadblocks in recruiting for today’s athlete. 

After coaching with and against the best in the college game for decades you live it. Now evaluating, ranking and interviewing the elite player you learn more. Studying NBA draft prospects you learn what the serious player does and stays away from.

Eliminate these from your daily routine and watch the progress begin.

Analysis on Boogie Fland:

Fland has an extra gear of speed which is evident. His burst and handle help him put extreme pressure on the defense in transition. 

In a halfcourt set, once Fland has made up his mind, he is one of the best in the class at getting a piece of the paint to either score or be a willing passer and spray it out to open teammates. 

He has a knack to find the open pocket of space for his pull up jumper. 

In ball-screens, he locates the coverage and reads the help. 

He displays control, vision and IQ coming off the ball-screen to manipulate a defense.

Fland is the 15th five-star point guard to commit to Kentucky since Hall of fame coach John Calipari took over in 2009. @ukcoachcalipari

Post-game analysis and my prediction for the Clemson Tigers after their win over Winthrop: 

1. The roster has scoring punch, versatile pieces and depth in case of foul trouble. They can play big or go small. 

2. Their identity is one of passing and scoring. Their roster possesses multiple 3-point shooters including Joe Girard III. It’s a group of ball movers and assist makers. (21 assist on 27 FG’s.) (13-23 from 3, 40%) 

3. Former ESPN 100 PJ Hall (20 points in 20 min) is the go to guy as he is stronger and healthy. Skilled to drill 3’s or score in the paint with post moves. Clemson will play through him as a playmaker or as a primary option. He must avoid foul trouble. 

4. Ian Schieffelin, Chauncey Wiggins, RJ Godfrey and Jack Clark give the Tigers size, rebounding, scoring and lineup versatility. 

5. A top 4 team in the ACC and NCAA bound!

It’s the Early Signing period in College Basketball.  Let's take a peek ahead and break down how -- and why -- these five committed recruits will impact their future programs. The entire report can be found on ESPN.com 

Cooper Flagg, Duke 
2024 ESPN Rank: No.1 
Look for Flagg to have Jayson Tatum-Paulo Banchero esque production as the focal point of Duke’s No. 1 recruiting class.

Flory Bidunga, Kansas
2024 ESPN 100 Rank: 6

Flory Bidunga will influence and fit the Jayhawks system and scheme from day one. He’s the most physically gifted big man in the country. He plays with power, force, and mobility on both ends inside the arc. 

Jalil Bethea, Miami
2024 ESPN 100 Rank: 7

 He shows a quick trigger and a willingness to work for quality shots. Beyond his natural talent, his impressive efficiency captures your attention and suggests an ability to make a quick impact. He made 62 3-pointers this summer at a 40% clip. His free throw percentage is 84% and his overall FG percentage is 49.8%. He does not settle for jumpers – he finds ways to change the scoreboard. 

Robert Wright, Baylor
2024 ESPN 100 Rank: 37

Wright is an organizer and highly competitive, which enhances his on-court skills as  a ball mover, playmaker and tenacious on-ball defender. He will score when needed and has what it takes both from mindset and ability standpoint. I would trust him to manage the responsibility because of his traits. 

Trent Perry USC
2024 ESPN 100 Rank: 42

As a playmaker, Perry is an accurate and willing passer who is a capable scorer and shooter from beyond the arc. Most freshmen arrive and press for their opportunities. Perry understands it’s about winning and knows how to both read the floor and process the game.
